{ White decides to resolve the central tension, because he's spotted some tactical weaknesses on d5 and b7. He also benefits from the black knight coming to d5, since it shields the d4-pawn from attack by the black queen  @@StartBracket@@which, in combination with the c6-knight and the g4-bishop, was starting to exert unpleasant pressure@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Nxd5 { Taking a central pawn while removing the attack on the c6-knight. }
8. Qb3
{ Initiating a very sharp tactical sequence. As often happens, such sequences can end up in simplifications and relatively dry positions, but both sides have opportunities to deviate. The alternative 8. Be2 is a safe @@StartBracket@@some might, correctly, say 'cowardly'@@EndBracket@@ line I've used on occasion. White will castle, play h3 and Qb3, and claim that his light initiative and lead in development counts for more than Black's superior structure. This line can be played with little or no preparation by both sides, and it is hardly a critical or threatening attempt. }
