{ So what's going on here? White has an extra doubled d-pawn. Although his structure is imperfect, the d-pawns control important central squares on the c- and e-files @@StartBracket@@for example, ...Nc6 and ...Be6 are ruled out, and the c5- and e5-squares are attractive spots for a white knight@@EndBracket@@. If White is allowed simply to consolidate the position, he'll certainly have an advantage, both in the structure as it stands and due to the space advantage and dynamic possibilities it offers. In particular, we'll see White playing d6 himself in many positions. This can be used tactically  @@StartBracket@@for instance, if there's a bishop on f3 which can capture on b7@@EndBracket@@, or to play a symmetrical IQP structure after ...exd6 where White's pieces are more actively placed. It can also be used to disrupt Black's position slightly @@StartBracket@@for example, ...Qxd6 might allow Nb5 with tempo@@EndBracket@@. Black has two basic approaches to this position @@StartBracket@@and also to related lines, for example after 8.Nge2@@EndBracket@@. The first, and most popular, is to build up pressure on the d5-pawn, with the aim of recapturing the pawn under favourable conditions. Often White won't aim to hold this pawn forever but instead forces Black to make concessions to regain it. The second plan involves playing for an endgame where Black hopes that the white pawns in the centre and on the queenside will provide ready targets. }
8... Nbd7
{ By far the most popular move, with almost 1, 400 games compared to 450 with  8...Na6  Black prepares to bring the knight to b6, to exert pressure on the d5-pawn. The knight also blocks the half-open b-file, allowing the c8-bishop to develop without dropping the b7-pawn. }
9. Nh3
{ The most accurate continuation, directly bringing the knight to f4. It's only been played in about 25 games compared to almost 1, 300 with 9. Bf3 but it's just a better move. This is also the reason why Sam Shankland assessed 8...Nbd7 as dubious and preferred 8...Na6 in his Lifetime Repertoires series.   After the far more popular  9.Bf3  Nb6  10.Nge2  Bg4!  is a good move, forcing  11.Bxg4  Nxg4  White's light-squared bishop has taken several moves to trade itself on  g4.  If Black wants to achieve a similar trade after 9. Nh3, White will be a tempo up. }
9... Nb6 10. Nf4 Bf5 11. O-O h6
{ This is a typical waiting move, making ...g5 a much more serious option by defending the pawn in advance. }
12. a4 a5
{ a4 and ...a5 is always a useful inclusion for White, who gains the b5-square for his knight and de-stabilises the b6-knight. Here my silicon co-authors have found a good move. }
13. h4
{ Now ...g5 would leave Black with a serious weakness on g5, so he should continue }
13... Qd6 14. Nb5 Qd8 15. Bf3 Rc8
{ Now, instead of allowing ...Nc4, White should transform the position with the typical exchange }
16. d6 exd6 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bf3
{ White retains his extra pawn for the moment. The game might continue } 18...
Qd7 { @@StartBracket@@threatening ...Nxa4@@EndBracket@@ } 19. Be2 Rfe8 20. Qd1
{ Black has some compensation but I don't think it's sufficient. White can play consolidating moves with Nc3 and Bd3, and can improve his rooks with Re1 or Ra3. }
